\begin{abstract}

Vehicular Federated Learning (VFL) emerged as a pivotal distributed machine learning paradigm, enabling the preservation of data privacy and reducing communication overhead. However, VFL faces unique challenges due to client heterogeneity, dynamic network topology, and limited communication bandwidth.
In this article, we propose the Federated Learning with Importance-driven Pruning and Selection (FLIPS) framework.
\alg{} introduces selective layer pruning guided by SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) to preserve essential model components while reducing communication costs.
FLIPS' multifactor client selection mechanism prioritizes participants based on communication quality, mobility, computational resources, and local data relevance, enhancing training efficiency.
We also introduce an importance-weighted aggregation at the server further improving model performance by prioritizing the aggregation of the most important model weights.
Evaluation over CIFAR-100 demonstrate that \alg{} achieves superior accuracy, faster convergence, and reduced communication overhead compared to baseline methods.
These results underscore the efficacy of \alg{} in dynamic and resource-constrained vehicular environments, paving the way for robust and scalable for VFL.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Model Pruning, Client Selection, SHAP, and Communication Efficiency.
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

\ac{FL} offers a promising alternative to enable a large set of applications ranging from predictive traffic management to autonomous driving, since \ac{FL} offers  collaborative \ac{ML} training through localized updates rather than raw data exchange. Despite its potential, deploying \ac{VFL} introduces unique challenges that existing \ac{FL} frameworks fail to address holistically \cite{pokhrel2020federated}. This is because \ac{VFL} environments are inherently dynamic and mobile, where vehicles exhibit  heterogeneity in computational resources, data distributions, and connectivity patterns.
Hence, conventional \ac{FL} struggles to maintain model accuracy and communication efficiency under these conditions, leading to unstable convergence or unsafe predictions in safety-critical \ac{VFL} scenarios.

In dynamic and heterogeneous \ac{VFL} environments, training a complete ML model is challenging due to mobility constraints and intermittent connectivity \cite{razmi2024board}. In this way,  model compression techniques are crucial for minimizing communication overhead and optimizing model transmission, ensuring better adaptation to \ac{VFL} scenarios while preserving critical model accuracy \cite{zhang2024distributed}. Current approaches prioritize isolated optimizations, leaving critical gaps unaddressed. Early studies, such as those optimizing latency in reliable vehicular communications, validate FL’s feasibility but simplify client dynamics and resource constraints, such as gradient quantization and sparsification, effectively reduce bandwidth consumption \cite{Zhang2024}. However, they typically apply uniform compression rates across all model layers, overlooking the varying significance of parameters in complex tasks such as pedestrian detection \cite{konevcny2016federated}. In contrast, non-uniform compression guided by \ac{XAI}  techniques, such as \ac{SHAP}, identifies and preserves high-impact parameters, ensuring that compression targets less critical components while maintaining model accuracy and interpretability \cite{DUBEY2025100697}.

Efficient client selection is essential for \ac{VFL}, requiring the consideration of vehicular-specific factors when determining which vehicles should participate in the federation \cite{nishio2019client,yang2021achieving}. For instance, transient connectivity, mobility, and data relevance influence model performance and training stability in dynamic vehicular environments. While \ac{XAI} approaches can enhance the model transmission, intelligent client selection ensures that high-impact vehicles contribute more effectively to the global model. However, existing approaches often fail to holistically integrate communication efficiency, client reliability, mobility-awareness and model interpretability, resulting in suboptimal trade-offs between accuracy, overhead, and convergence time in dynamic vehicular networks.

To address these challenges, we introduce \alg{}, a \ac{FL} framework that integrates adaptive model compression, intelligent client selection, and explainability-driven aggregation algorithms to enhance efficiency and robustness in \ac{VFL} scenarios. 
Specifically, \alg{} leverages SHAP-derived importance scores to implement non-uniform layer pruning, selectively compressing less impactful parameters while preserving critical ones. 
\alg{} also introduces an intelligent client selection mechanism that dynamically evaluates computational resources, mobility, real-time connectivity metrics, and data relevance. 
Finally, \alg{} leverages layer-wise importance scores to weight global model updates, ensuring that the most influential vehicles and parameters contribute more significantly to the learning process. Simulation results using NS-3 validate our approach, showing that \alg{} reduces communication overhead by 48\% compared to FedAvg while improving accuracy by 14\% over FedProx in mobile scenarios, setting a new state-of-the-art for vehicular federated learning.

To address key challenges in VFL, this article discusses the following research questions:
\begin{inparaenum}[i)]
    \item  How can SHAP-guided selective layer pruning reduce communication overhead while preserving essential model components in dynamic environments? 
    \item  How a multi-criteria client selection approach (e.g., connectivity, mobility, computational resources, and data relevance) optimizes training efficiency and robustness in heterogeneous VFL scenarios?
    \item  How can importance-weighted aggregation based on SHAP scores enhance global model performance over traditional federated averaging?
    \item Can a unified framework combining adaptive pruning, multifactor client selection, and explainability-driven aggregation achieve faster convergence and higher accuracy in resource-constrained VFL settings? The FLIPS framework addresses these questions by using SHAP-based pruning to prioritize key layers, context-aware client selection to minimize dropouts, and weighted aggregation to emphasize impactful updates, thereby balancing communication efficiency and model robustness.
\end{inparaenum}


The remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Section~\ref{sec:related_work} reviews related works. Sections~\ref{sec:system_model} and~\ref{sec:algorithm} detail the system model and \alg{}’s design. Section~\ref{sec:experiments} presents experimental results, and Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes.

\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related_work}

Reducing communication overhead is critical in \ac{VFL}, particularly in mobile scenarios. Current works introduced compression techniques, such as quantized gradient exchanges and sparsification, to enhance model transmission. In our previous work \cite{10503481}, we proposed DrivePFL, a FL approach that selectively transmits only the most critical model layers based on mobility predictions. While DrivePFL improved communication efficiency and model convergence, challenges in explainability-driven aggregation and client selection under dynamic conditions remained.

Lee \et{} \cite{Lee_Zhang_Avestimehr_2023} introduced FedLAMA, a FL proposal that adjusts the aggregation interval on a layer-wise basis, considering model discrepancy and communication cost. This approach effectively reduces communication overhead while maintaining model accuracy. However, to enhance FedLAMA’s efficiency in dynamic and non-iid vehicle environments, further advancements are needed, including explainability-driven pruning schemes.

Konečný \et{} \cite{konevcny2016federated} demonstrated how structured and sketched updates reduce uplink costs, while Sattler \et{} \cite{sattler2019robust} explored sparse ternary compression. However, despite their effectiveness in \ac{FL} environments, these methods typically apply uniform compression across all model layers, assuming equal importance. In \ac{VFL}, where latency and reliability constraints are more severe, uniform compression can over-compress crucial layers, leading to suboptimal performance and accuracy degradation.

Efficient client selection remains a fundamental challenge in \ac{VFL}, as suboptimal choices can compromise both training convergence and communication efficiency. FedCS \cite{nishio2019client} selects participants based on resource constraints and attempts to increase the number of active clients each round.
Yang \et{} \cite{yang2021achieving} incorporated energy constraints into the selection mechanism, thereby improving sustainability in mobile \ac{FL}.
However, these approaches do not consider key factors to \ac{VFL} settings, including mobility and data relevance. Consequently, dropout rates and communication overhead can remain high if vehicles with poor connectivity or minimal relevant data are routinely selected.

The SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) method, introduced by Lundberg and Lee~\cite{lundberg2017unified}, provides a game-theoretic approach to interpret machine learning model predictions by assigning importance values to individual features. SHAP quantifies each feature's contribution to the difference between a model's prediction and a baseline expectation.
In FL, SHAP's ability to identify critical parameters can be leveraged to optimize communication and computation.
The usage of SHAP in FL can enable efficient, explainability-driven aggregation by weighting updates based on their inferred impact, fostering robust collaboration in distributed settings.

The Federated Learning of Explainable AI (FED-XAI) framework is designed to preserve privacy during the collaborative training of AI models in secure VFL scenarios \cite{info13080395, Fed-XAI}. In addition to ensuring privacy, FED-XAI enhances the explainability of both individual models and the aggregated global model resulting from FL. The main objective of FED-XAI is to predict the Quality of Experience (QoE) perceived by vehicles and enhance video data transmission in VFL environments. Similarly, the FLaaS framework introduces flexible mechanisms for B5G/6G networks, enabling end users to leverage FL services \cite{CORCUERABARCENA2023356}. Additionally, FLaaS presents a QoE-forecasting application based on a vehicular networking use case. However, both FED-XAI and FLaaS do not incorporate model compression, client selection, or mechanisms for fast convergence in resource-constrained VFL settings.

The integration of XAI and FL aims to enhance the effectiveness and trustworthiness of trajectory decisions for newcomer Autonomous Vehicles (AVs) \cite{9824617}. When a newcomer vehicle requests assistance with trajectory planning, the edge server initiates a federated learning process to train a distributed, collaborative model for trajectory and velocity prediction. XAI is then used to quantify the contribution of each feature provided by participating vehicles to the overall system. However, the proposed scheme lacks efficiency in terms of communication overhead and model transmission optimization.

In contrast, FLIPS specifically harnesses importance measure - similar to those used in XAI methods (e.g., SHAP-like indicators identifying the most critical parameters or layers) - to guide the pruning process. Rather than focusing on human-interpretable explanations, FLIPS systematically computes a layer-level importance score to determine which model segments are essential to retain. This explainability-driven approach ensures that model pruning and aggregation prioritize parameters with the highest impact on performance, effectively balancing communication efficiency with minimal accuracy loss. Unlike studies that solely emphasize interpretability, FLIPS repurposes these importance scores to actively optimize the \ac{FL} pipeline, enabling more efficient federation in resource-constrained vehicular networks.

Based on the state-of-the-art analysis, we conclude that the existing \ac{VFL} literature offers significant contributions in areas such as latency optimization, compression, client selection, and interpretability. However, existing approaches fail to holistically integrate communication efficiency, client reliability, and model interpretability, leading to suboptimal trade-offs between accuracy, overhead, and scalability in dynamic vehicular networks.
To the best of our knowledge, most approaches tackle these issues independently, failing to unify them under a single, cohesive strategy for \ac{VFL} environment.



\section{System Model}
\label{sec:system_model}

The system consists of a set of vehicles $\mathcal{V} = \{1, 2, \dots, V\}$, a set of base stations $\mathcal{B} = \{1, 2, \dots, B\}$, and a central \ac{FL} server. 
In this scenario, vehicles are equipped with wireless antennas, such as, \ac{mmWave}, to enable high-speed data transmission with \ac{mmWave} base stations.
The communication link between vehicle $v$ and base station $b$ has a data rate $R_{v,b}$, which is influenced by channel conditions, bandwidth, and transmission power factors.
Total communication delay $T_{\text{comm}}$ is a function of the data rates and model size updates.

Each vehicle $v \in \mathcal{V}$  maintains its private local dataset $\mathcal{D}_v = \{(x_i^v, y_i^v)\}_{i=1}^{N_v}$, where $x_i^v$ represents the input features and $y_i^v$ the corresponding labels, while the local dataset size is denoted as $N_v = |\mathcal{D}_v|$.
The local dataset $\mathcal{D}_v$ significantly varies in size, feature distribution, and label distribution, typically showing non-\ac{IID} characteristics.
Furthermore, each vehicle $v$ is equipped with an \ac{OBU} capable of performing local computations required for training \ac{ML} model $\mathbf{w}_v$ with \( L \) layers denoted as $\mathcal{L} = \{l_1,l_2,\dots,l_L\}$.

At the beginning of each communication round $t$, the central server broadcasts the current global model parameters $\mathbf{w}^{(t)}$ to all participating clients.
Each vehicle $v$ trains a local model $\mathbf{w}_v$ by minimizing its loss function $L_{v}(\mathbf{w})$ over its dataset $\mathcal{D}_v$ using a specified number of epochs $E$. The model parameters are updated iteratively through \ac{SGD} with a learning rate $\eta$, as defined in Eq. \ref{eq:sgd}.

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{w}_k^{(t)} = \mathbf{w}^{(t)} - \eta \nabla L_k(\mathbf{w}^{(t)}),
    \label{eq:sgd}
\end{equation}

The local train aims to minimize the local loss function $\ell(\mathbf{w}; x_i, y_i)$ on a single data sample $(x_i, y_i)$, as shown in Eq. \ref{eq:local_loss}.
The loss function $L_v(\mathbf{w})$ is defined as the average loss, as the prediction error, across all predictions for the dataset $\mathcal{D}_v$ using the model weights $W$.

\begin{equation}
L_{v}(\mathbf{w})
=\frac{1}{N_v}
  \sum_{i=1}^{N_v}
  \ell\bigl(\mathbf{w};\,x_i^{v},\,y_i^{v}\bigr),
\label{eq:local_loss}
\end{equation}

Afterwards, clients report their local model updates, and the central server orchestrates the \ac{VFL} process by aggregating local model updates from the vehicles, and also maintains a global model with parameters $\mathbf{w}$.
The central server relies on an aggregation function, such as \ac{FedAvg}, to update the global model based on the received local models. This process iterates over multiple communication rounds until convergence. 

\section{\alg{} Framework}
\label{sec:algorithm}

In this section, we present a VFL framework for dynamic and mobile environments that integrates adaptive model compression, client selection, and explainability-driven aggregation algorithms, called as \alg{}. Specifically, we propose an adaptive client selection algorithm that considers communication quality, mobility, computational capacity, and data volume to select clients for the FL training process, thereby improving the efficiency of model aggregation \cite{nishio2019client}. \alg{} also supports a layer-wise model pruning to mitigate computational and communication overheads, where
layers of higher importance, identified through SHAP-based analysis, undergo less pruning to retain essential features. Finally, \alg{} combines model updates with quantization and pruning techniques, significantly reducing the transmitted data volume and enhancing communication efficiency in VFL mobile environments. We refine the aggregation process further through SHAP-enhanced aggregation, which uses importance-weighted model updates derived from SHAP values~\cite{lundberg2017unified}. Figure~\ref{fig:system_model} illustrates the main components of \alg{} under a \ac{VFL} scenario.

