\subsection{Problem definition}

% \sid{TEMOS QUE COLOCAR AO LONGO DAS SUB-SECS A IMPORTÂNCIA DE PREDIÇÃO DE MOBILIDADE E DIREÇÃO.}

The \alg{} framework aims to address the challenges inherent in dynamic and resource-constrained \ac{VFL} environments, where clients exhibit varying computational capacities/connectivity and data distributions. For instance, dropout rates and communication overhead can remain high if vehicles with poor connectivity or minimal relevant data are routinely selected.

Furthermore, in \ac{VFL}, client vehicles are inherently mobile, leading to dynamic network topologies and intermittent connectivity. Predicting mobility patterns and direction is critical to ensure stable participation in the federation. Vehicles with unpredictable trajectories or short contact times with base stations risk abrupt disconnections, causing incomplete model updates and wasted resources. For instance, a vehicle moving away from the network coverage area may fail to transmit its updates, while another approaching a cluster of base stations could offer prolonged connectivity. By integrating mobility prediction into client selection, \alg{} prioritizes vehicles with stable trajectories and sufficient contact time, minimizing dropout rates and maximizing reliable contributions. Furthermore, anticipating directional changes allows proactive resource allocation, ensuring timely model exchanges before clients exit the coverage zone. This approach enhances training efficiency and robustness in highly dynamic vehicular environments, where traditional \ac{FL} frameworks struggle with transient participants.

We define a vehicle-specific weight \(\zeta_{v} = I_{v} \, N_{v} \cdot \tau_{v,b}\) to capture dataset size, SHAP-based importance, and predicted contact time, where \(I_{v}\) aggregates per-layer importance scores and \(\tau_{v,b}\) is the predicted contact time between vehicle \(v\) and base station \(b\). Hence, \alg{}'s objective function in round \(t\) is defined in Eq.~\ref{eq:objective}.

\begin{equation}
\min_{\mathbf{w}}
L_{\mathrm{FLIPS}}(\mathbf{w})
=
\sum_{v \,\in\, \mathcal{S}_t}
\zeta_{v}\;
L_{v}(\mathbf{w}).
\label{eq:objective}
\end{equation}


Vehicles with stronger link quality, larger datasets, and stable connectivity (higher \(\tau_{v,b}\)) receive higher influence. After local training, each vehicle prunes its updated parameters according to SHAP-derived layer importance, and then uploads the pruned model \(\tilde{\mathbf{w}}_{v}^{(t)}\) to the server. The global model update for layer \(l\) is computed based on Eq. \ref{eq:global}.

\begin{equation}
\mathbf{w}^{l,(t+1)}
=
\frac{\displaystyle
      \sum_{v \,\in\, \mathcal{S}_t}
      \zeta_{v}\,
      \tilde{\mathbf{w}}_{v}^{l,(t)}
     }
     {\displaystyle
      \sum_{v \,\in\, \mathcal{S}_t}
      \zeta_{v}
     }.
\label{eq:global}
\end{equation}

\alg{} ensures that valuable updates are aggregated reliably by emphasizing vehicles with stable links, high SHAP importance, and prolonged connectivity. In this sense, \alg{} adapts to vehicular conditions by reducing the impact of poor connectivity and prioritizing parameters critical to the global model, ultimately finding while respecting communication constraints such as limited coverage and frequent handovers, as denoted in Eq. \ref{eq:flips}.

\begin{equation}
\mathbf{w}^{*}
=
\arg\min_{\mathbf{w}}
L_{\mathrm{FLIPS}}(\mathbf{w})
\label{eq:flips}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Layer Importance Evaluation Using \ac{SHAP}}
\label{sec:shap_evaluation}

After local training, each client $k$ assesses the significance of individual model layers using the \ac{SHAP} algorithm~\cite{lundberg2017unified}. 
Unlike standard feature-based explanations, we treat entire layers as ``features,'' computing how each layer contributes to model performance for given local data. 
This evaluation is essential not only for adaptive model pruning but also for importance-weighted model aggregation. 

Deep SHAP computes \cite{bialek2022dataset} layer-level SHAP values by interpreting each layer as a ``player'' in a cooperative game.
For a model with layers $\mathcal{L} = \{1,2,\dots,L\}$, the SHAP value $\phi_k^l(x_i)$ for layer $l$ at client $k$ and sample $x_i$ captures the contribution of layer $l$ to the deviation of the model's output from a baseline prediction, which is formally defined on Eq. \ref{eq:baseline_shap}. We denote $S$ as any subset of layers excluding layer $l$, and $f_S(\cdot)$ denotes the model's output when only layers in $S$ are active.

\begin{equation}
\phi_k^l(x_i) 
= \sum_{S \subseteq \mathcal{L} \setminus \{l\}} 
\frac{|S|!(|\mathcal{L}| - |S| - 1)!}{|\mathcal{L}|!}
\Bigl[ 
    f_S(x_i) - f_{S \cup \{l\}}(x_i) 
\Bigr],
\label{eq:baseline_shap}
\end{equation}

We obtain a SHAP-based importance score $I_k^l$ by averaging over a local validation set $\mathcal{D}_k^{\mathrm{val}}$, as defined in Eq. \ref{eq:layer_shap_score}.
In this sense, higher magnitudes of $I_k^l$ imply that layer $l$ plays a more crucial role in the client's local model predictions.

\begin{equation}
I_k^l 
= \frac{1}{|\mathcal{D}_k^{\mathrm{val}}|}
  \sum_{(x_i, y_i)\in \mathcal{D}_k^{\mathrm{val}}}
  \bigl|\phi_k^l(x_i)\bigr|.
\label{eq:layer_shap_score}
\end{equation}

Directly recomputing \ac{SHAP} values every round can be prohibitively expensive.
Moreover, vehicular conditions (\eg, frequent handovers, variable link quality) cause a single client's updates to become stale or arrive late. To address these issues, we propose an \emph{incremental} and \emph{context-aware} extension to Deep SHAP, ensuring the final importance scores integrate both network reliability and model changes over time.

Let $\mathbf{w}_{\text{base}}^{(t)}$ denote the lightweight ``baseline'' model maintained by the server (\eg, an exponentially-smoothed version of the previous global model). Each vehicle $k$ computes a \emph{delta} vector to reflect the changes since the last baseline, as shown in Eq. \ref{eq:lightweight}

\begin{equation}
\Delta \mathbf{w}^{(t)} 
= \mathbf{w}^{(t)} 
  - \mathbf{w}_{\text{base}}^{(t)},
\label{eq:lightweight}
\end{equation}

In this context, each vehicle incrementally adjusts its previous round's SHAP values $\phi_k^l(x_i)$ by measuring how $\Delta \mathbf{w}^{(t)}$ influences local predictions $\Delta \phi_k^l(x_i)$. The local predictions $\Delta \phi_k^l(x_i)$ are computed based on Eq. \ref{eq:local}.

\begin{equation}
\Delta \phi_k^l(x_i) 
= \mathrm{SHAP}\bigl(
   \mathbf{w}_{\text{base}}^{(t)},\, 
   \Delta \mathbf{w}^{(t)},\, 
   x_i,\, 
   l
  \bigr).
  \label{eq:local}
\end{equation}

The local SHAP value is updated based on Eq. \ref{eq:SHAP}, where clients need only evaluate the \emph{incremental contribution} of newly updated layers, drastically reducing computational overhead while preserving the interpretability benefits of SHAP.

\begin{equation}
\phi_k^l(x_i) 
\;\leftarrow\; \phi_k^l(x_i) + \Delta \phi_k^l(x_i).
\label{eq:SHAP}
\end{equation}

We introduce a context factor $\omega_k \in (0,1]$ for each vehicle $k$ to further mitigate the risk of stale or partially transmitted updates. This factor downscales importance scores $I_k^l$ when the vehicle suffers adverse conditions (\eg, low $\mathrm{RSSI}$, repeated timeouts), as defined on Eq. \ref{eq:contextualized_score}.

\begin{equation}
I_k^l 
= \omega_k 
  \times \frac{1}{|\mathcal{D}_k^{\mathrm{val}}|}
  \sum_{(x_i, y_i)\in \mathcal{D}_k^{\mathrm{val}}} 
  \bigl|\phi_k^l(x_i)\bigr|.
\label{eq:contextualized_score}
\end{equation}

For instance, we define $\omega_k$ as a measure capturing link quality, reliability, and predicted mobility, as shown in Eq.~\ref{eq:omega}. Here, $\mathrm{RSSI}_k^{\mathrm{norm}}$ is a normalized measure of signal strength, $\mathrm{dropout}_k$ accumulates recent communication failures, and $\tilde{\tau}_{k,b}$ represents the predicted contact time. Coefficients $\gamma_1$, $\gamma_2$, and $\gamma_3$ weight the importance of link quality, reliability, and mobility prediction, respectively.

\begin{equation}
\omega_k 
= \min\Bigl\{1,\,
   \gamma_1\,\mathrm{RSSI}_k^{\mathrm{norm}}
   + \gamma_2\,\frac{1}{1 + \mathrm{dropout}_k} 
      + \gamma_3\,\tilde{\tau}_{k,b}
  \Bigr\},
  \label{eq:omega}
\end{equation}

The final importance score $I_k^l$ drives the selective layer pruning and server-side aggregation. For instance, layers with smaller $I_k^l$ receive higher pruning thresholds, cutting more weights to reduce communication overhead. In this sense, critical layers are preserved even in constrained \ac{VFL} environments.
We denote $\tilde{\mathbf{w}}_k^{l,(t)}$ as the pruned weights from client $k$, which is defined on Eq. \ref{Eq:prune}. Hence, vehicles with higher layer importance and stable network conditions shape the global model more strongly, enhancing robustness against partially delivered or outdated updates.
    
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{w}^{l,(t+1)} 
    = \frac{\sum_{k=1}^K \Bigl(I_k^l\,N_k\Bigr) \,\tilde{\mathbf{w}}_k^{l,(t)}}
           {\sum_{k=1}^K I_k^l\,N_k},
    \label{Eq:prune}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Explainability Analysis}
\label{sec:explainability}

To quantify the contribution of individual model layers to prediction accuracy, SHAP values were computed for each layer across clients. Layer-level SHAP scores were derived by interpreting each layer as a cooperative player in the model’s prediction process, with contributions measured as deviations from a baseline output. The magnitude of SHAP values, averaged over local validation datasets, identified layers critical to maintaining model performance. For example, convolutional layers processing spatial features exhibited higher importance scores compared to fully connected layers, reflecting their role in extracting vehicular-relevant patterns such as motion trajectories or sensor data. 

Figure~\ref{fig:shap_layers} shows SHAP values across model layers to quantify layer contributions, where convolutional layers processing raw sensor inputs show highest importance.
Results demonstrate that initial convolutional layers (Conv1-3) exhibit higher importance scores for processing raw sensor inputs, while later layers show reduced impact. 
Figure \ref{fig:shap_heatmap} reveals temporal consistency in layer importance rankings across communication rounds, with GPS-processing layers maintaining stable high values.
Results revels that GPS-processing layers (L3-L5) maintain consistent high importance.


