Mobility and direction prediction are pivotal in \ac{VFL} to mitigate communication disruptions caused by vehicular movement. For example, a vehicle traveling at high speed toward the edge of a base station’s coverage area may disconnect mid-transmission, while one moving along a predictable route within dense urban infrastructure can maintain stable links. Accurately forecasting these patterns enables the server to select clients with sufficient contact time for complete model exchanges, reducing partial updates and stragglers. The Kalman filter is particularly suited for this task, as it efficiently estimates future positions and velocities despite measurement noise from GPS or onboard sensors. By analyzing a vehicle’s trajectory, \alg{} predicts its dwell time within communication range, dynamically adjusting client selection weights. This ensures that participants likely to remain connected throughout the training round are prioritized, while those with erratic paths or impending handovers are deprioritized. Such context-aware selection is indispensable in \ac{VFL}, where mobility directly impacts both communication reliability and the quality of federated updates.

To handle vehicular mobility, each client $k$ maintains an internal Kalman filter to predict its position and velocity over short time horizons. Define the state vector:
\[
\mathbf{x}_k(t) \;=\; 
\begin{bmatrix}
p_x \\[0.3em]
p_y \\[0.3em]
v_x \\[0.3em]
v_y
\end{bmatrix},
\]
representing the vehicle’s 2D position $(p_x,p_y)$ and velocity $(v_x,v_y)$. The state evolves according to
\[
\mathbf{x}_k(t+1) = \mathbf{F}\,\mathbf{x}_k(t) \;+\; \mathbf{w}_k(t),
\]
where $\mathbf{F}$ is the state-transition matrix (assuming constant velocity or a simple motion model), and $\mathbf{w}_k(t)$ is process noise.

At each timestep, the client receives GPS (or other localization) measurements
\[
\mathbf{z}_k(t) = \mathbf{H}\,\mathbf{x}_k(t) \;+\; \mathbf{r}_k(t),
\]
where $\mathbf{H}$ is the observation matrix and $\mathbf{r}_k(t)$ is measurement noise. The standard Kalman filter recursion yields an \emph{a posteriori} state estimate $\widehat{\mathbf{x}}_k(t)$ and covariance $\mathbf{P}_k(t)$. Using these estimates, client $k$ can predict its future trajectory $\widehat{\mathbf{x}}_k(t+\Delta)$ for a short horizon $\Delta$.

Given a base station $b$ with coverage radius $r_b$, the \emph{predicted contact time} $\tau_{k,b}$ is approximated by the time until the vehicle’s position estimate leaves the coverage region. A simple discrete-time estimate is:
\[
\tau_{k,b} \approx 
\max\!\bigl( 0,\; \tfrac{ \|\mathbf{p}_k(t) - \mathbf{b}\| - r_b }{\|\mathbf{v}_k(t)\|} \bigr),
\]
where $\mathbf{p}_k(t)$ and $\mathbf{v}_k(t)$ are the position and velocity extracted from the Kalman filter’s current estimate, and $\mathbf{b}$ denotes the base station’s location. The client then normalizes $\tau_{k,b}$ for reporting:
\[
\widetilde{\tau}_{k,b} = \frac{\tau_{k,b}}{\tau_{\max}},
\]
where $\tau_{\max}$ is a reference maximum contact time (e.g., the longest feasible dwell time in the simulation).

\subsection{Algorithm Description}

\begin{algorithm}
\SetAlgoLined
\DontPrintSemicolon
\KwIn{Initial global model $\mathbf{w}^{(0)}$, client set $\mathcal{V}$, total rounds $T$, 
    \hspace{2.2cm}base station set $\mathcal{B}$, pruning base threshold $\theta_{\text{base}}$}
\KwOut{Optimized global model $\mathbf{w}^{(T)}$}
\For{$t \leftarrow 1$ \KwTo $T$}{
    \textbf{Server executes:}\;
    \textbf{1. Client Selection:}\;
    \ForEach{client $v \in \mathcal{V}$}{
        Predict contact time $\tau_{v,b}$ via Kalman filter (Sec. 4.6)\;
        Compute $\widetilde{\tau}_{v,b} = \frac{\tau_{v,b}}{\tau_{\max}}$\;
        Compute context factor $\omega_v$ using Eq.~\ref{eq:omega}\;
        Calculate normalized metrics: $\widetilde{A}_v$, $\widetilde{N}_v$\;
        Compute selection score $S_v$ using Eq.~\ref{eq:score}\;
    }
    Select subset $\mathcal{S}_t \leftarrow \underset{v \in \mathcal{V}}{\text{topK}} \left(S_v\right)$ with $\text{RSSI}_v \geq \text{RSSI}_{\text{min}}$\;
    
    \textbf{2. Model Broadcast:}\;
    Send $\mathbf{w}^{(t)}$ to all selected clients $v \in \mathcal{S}_t$\;
    
    \textbf{3. Client Updates (parallel execution):}\;
    \ForEach{client $v \in \mathcal{S}_t$}{
        Local training: $\mathbf{w}_v^{(t)} \leftarrow \text{SGD}(\mathbf{w}^{(t)}, \mathcal{D}_v, E)$\;
        Compute layer importance $I_v^l$ via SHAP (Eqs. \ref{eq:baseline_shap}-\ref{eq:contextualized_score})\;
        \ForEach{layer $l \in \mathcal{L}$}{
            Calculate pruning threshold $\theta_v^l$ using Eq.~\ref{eq:threshold}\;
            Prune weights: $\tilde{\mathbf{w}}_v^l \leftarrow \text{Prune}(\mathbf{w}_v^l, \theta_v^l)$\;
        }
        Quantize $\tilde{\mathbf{w}}_v$ and compress\;
        Send $(\tilde{\mathbf{w}}_v, I_v^l, N_v)$ to server\;
    }
    
    \textbf{4. Importance-Weighted Aggregation:}\;
    \ForEach{layer $l \in \mathcal{L}$}{
        $\mathbf{w}^{l,(t+1)} \leftarrow \frac{\sum_{v \in \mathcal{S}_t} I_v^l N_v \tilde{\mathbf{w}}_v^l}{\sum_{v \in \mathcal{S}_t} I_v^l N_v}$ \tcp*{Eq.~\ref{eq:update}}
    }
    Update global model $\mathbf{w}^{(t+1)} \leftarrow \{\mathbf{w}^{l,(t+1)}\}_{l=1}^L$\;
}
\caption{FLIPS Algorithm with Mobility Prediction}\label{alg:flips}
\end{algorithm}

The FLIPS algorithm operates in rounds (line 3) to optimize a global model $\mathbf{w}^{(T)}$. In each round $t$, the server performs four key phases:
(lines 5--12): For each client $v \in \mathcal{V}$ (line 6), the server predicts contact time $\tau_{v,b}$ using a Kalman filter (line 7), computes the normalized predicted contact time $\widetilde{\tau}_{v,b}$, and then calculates a context factor $\omega_v$ using Eq.~\ref{eq:omega} which incorporates $\widetilde{\tau}_{v,b}$ (line 8). The server then normalizes other metrics $\widetilde{A}_v$, $\widetilde{N}_v$ (line 9), and calculates a selection score $S_v$ (line 10). The top-$K$ clients with sufficient RSSI are selected into $\mathcal{S}_t$ (line 12).
(line 14--15): The server sends the current global model $\mathbf{w}^{(t)}$ to all selected clients (line 15).
(lines 17--27): Each client $v \in \mathcal{S}_t$ (line 18) locally trains $\mathbf{w}_v^{(t)}$ via SGD for $E$ epochs (line 19), computes layer-wise importance scores $I_v^l$ using SHAP (line 20), which now factor in mobility through $\omega_v$, and prunes each layer $l$ using adaptive thresholds $\theta_v^l$ (lines 21--24). The pruned weights $\tilde{\mathbf{w}}_v$ are quantized, compressed (line 25), and transmitted to the server (line 26).
(lines 29--33): The server aggregates pruned weights layer-wise (line 31), weighted by $I_v^l$ (now mobility-aware via $\widetilde{\tau}_{v,b}$) and data size $N_v$, to update the global model (line 33).

\subsubsection{Complexity Analysis}

Let $V = |\mathcal{V}|$, $K = |\mathcal{S}_t|$, $L = |\mathcal{L}|$, $P$ be the model size, and $E$ local epochs. Client selection costs $O(V(L + \log V))$ per round (Kalman filter, score computation, and top-$K$ selection). Client updates dominate with $O(K(E|\mathcal{D}_v| + L(P/L + \text{SHAP}))$ per client, where SHAP complexity depends on approximation methods. Aggregation requires $O(KLP/L) = O(KP)$. Overall, the algorithm has $O(T(V\log V + K(E|\mathcal{D}_v| + P + L\cdot\text{SHAP})))$ time complexity, dominated by client-side computations and linear in $T$ and $K$.


\section{Evaluation}
\label{sec:experiments}

In this section, we evaluate the performance of the  \alg{} compared with several well-known \ac{FL} algorithms to demonstrate its effectiveness in terms of communication efficiency, model accuracy, and convergence speed.
The experiments aim to highlight the benefits of selective layer pruning, multifactor client selection, and \ac{SHAP}-based importance weighting.

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

We considered the NS-3.43 network simulator\footnote{ns-3: \url{https://www.nsnam.org/}} integrated with TensorFlow and Keras\footnote{TensorFlow: \url{https://www.tensorflow.org/}} to implement and run the various \ac{FL} algorithms in a \ac{VFL} scenario. The integration allowed us to simulate realistic communication scenarios alongside deep learning processes, where TensorFlow and Keras handled model training and inference. 
We simulated an \ac{VFL} environment with a set of $K=50$ clients, and clients are heterogeneous in terms of data distribution, computational capabilities, and communication conditions.
Each vehicle moves following mobility patterns generated by SUMO\footnote{SUMO: \url{https://www.eclipse.org/sumo/}} in a Manhattan grid layout, simulating traffic dynamics and connectivity fluctuations within a structured urban environment.
The mobility model combined with ns-3’s created a comprehensive scenario to capture the challenges of dynamic connectivity, variable data distributions, and fluctuating network conditions. We repeated each simulation scenario 33 times to ensure statistical significance, and results were averaged, providing robust performance evaluations of the algorithms under study.

The experiments consider the CIFAR-100 dataset, 
which consists of 100 classes, each containing 600 images, resulting in a more fine-grained classification task.
This dataset is suitable for evaluating FL algorithms in scenarios requiring higher levels of granularity and complexity in image classification.
We consider data with non-IID characteristics to introduce data heterogeneity, ensuring a realistic representation of data distribution as commonly expected in many FL applications. We employed the Dirichlet distribution with a concentration parameter of  $\alpha = 0.5$, providing a realistic balance between heterogeneity and uniformity, appropriately reflecting the diversity of data in vehicular environments \cite{li2021model}. Hence, this partitioning approach allowed us to rigorously evaluate the robustness and performance of the proposed \alg{} framework and the baseline methods under challenging conditions of data imbalance and non-\ac{IID} distributions.

The global model used in our experiments is a custom 5-layer \ac{CNN}, which is defined as follows. The input layer accepts images of size 32×32×3. The first convolutional layer employs 32 filters of size 3×3 with stride 1, followed by a rectified linear unit (ReLU) activation and a 2×2 max pooling operation. The second convolutional layer consists of 64 filters of size 3×3, again followed by ReLU activation and a 2×2 max pooling layer. The third convolutional layer utilizes 128 filters of size 3×3, with subsequent ReLU activation and a 2×2 max pooling layer. The output from the convolutional layers is flattened and passed to a fully connected layer comprising 256 neurons with ReLU activation. The final layer is a softmax layer whose number of neurons corresponds to the number of classes in the dataset.

We compared the performance of two variants of the \alg{} algorithm: one with the usage of mobility prediction as a factor for client selection (denoted as FLIPS w/ MP) and one which uses RSSI rather than mobility prediction (denoted as FLIPS w/o MP).
The \alg{} algorithm is compared against 5 \ac{FL} frameworks, namely, \ac{FedAvg}, \ac{FedProx}, \ac{FedLAMA}, centralized learning, and local learning.
Specifically, centralized learning involves aggregating all data from distributed clients at the central server, where it assumes unrestricted data sharing and centralized computational resources.
Local learning refers to the scenario where each client trains its model independently using only its local data, \ie, without any communication or parameter sharing with other clients or a central server.
\ac{FedAvg} is a baseline \ac{FL} algorithm that combines local model updates with periodic averaging \cite{mcmahan2017communication}.
\ac{FedProx} extends \ac{FedAvg} by introducing a proximal term to the local objective functions, which  penalize deviations from the global model during local updates. This effectively addresses issues arising from varying data distributions and computational capabilities among clients \cite{li2018federated}.
\ac{FedLAMA} adjusts the aggregation intervals of model layers in a layer-wise manner, where it determines optimal synchronization frequencies for each layer, allowing for reduced communication without significantly impacting model accuracy.
Finally, \alg{} relies on instantaneous network conditions and client resource availability for selection, as introduced in Section 4. 

