By analyzing the results, we conclude that FedAvg confirms that conventional FL methods require fundamental redesign for \ac{FL} environments. On the other hand, FLIPS achieves better performance through three synergistic mechanisms: 1) client selection avoiding unstable nodes, 2) adaptive compression based on predicted channel capacity, and 3) dynamic parameter pruning during network congestion ($\rho_b > 0.8$).


Figure~\ref{fig:network_perf} compares model transmission times under varying network traffic loads (10\%, 50\%, and 100\%), showing both the first and last client completion times. 
The results reveal that \alg{} w/ MP demonstrated significantly faster model transmission than baseline algorithms across all traffic conditions, \ie, the server must not wait for slow learners (a.k.a., stragglers) in each communication round, since straggler clients delay the overall FL execution.
At 10\% traffic, \alg{} w/ MP achieved first-client completion in $11.13 \pm 0.41$s, 5.9$\times$ faster than FedAvg ($66.07 \pm 10.17$s), while the last-client completion time for \alg{} w/ MP ($22.34 \pm 0.79$s) was 4.1$\times$ faster than FedAvg ($91.57 \pm 11.31$s). This gap widened under heavier loads: at 100\% traffic, \alg{} w/ MP maintained first-client completion in $19.31 \pm 0.60$s, compared to $114.75 \pm 7.01$s for FedAvg---a 5.9$\times$ improvement. Notably, FedAvg and FedLAMA consistently reached the 120s simulation timeout limit for last-client completion at full network load, indicating frequent failure to synchronize all clients under congestion. FLIPS achieves substantially faster transmission times at all load levels, with FedAvg and FedLAMA reaching simulation timeouts (120s) for last-client completion at 100\% load.

 



\section{Conclusions}
\label{sec:conclusion}

This article presents \alg{}, a VFL framework that integrates adaptive model compression, intelligent client selection, and explainability-driven aggregation to enhance efficiency and robustness in vehicular federated learning environments. By leveraging SHAP-based importance evaluation, selective layer pruning, and a client selection mechanism, \alg{} significantly reduces communication overhead in mobile and dynamic scenarios while maintaining critical model accuracy. Simulation results show that FLIPS not only achieves accuracy levels comparable to centralized learning but also surpasses baseline methods such as FedAvg, FedProx, and FedLAMA in terms of convergence speed and communication efficiency. These findings highlight FLIPS' robustness in handling heterogeneous data distributions, dynamic network conditions, and bandwidth constraints inherent to vehicular networks

The success of FLIPS lies in its holistic approach, where it judiciously prunes model layers based on their importance, selects clients using multiple relevant criteria, and aggregates updates in an importance-weighted manner. This integrated strategy ensures that the most impactful model updates are prioritized, leading to faster convergence and reduced model transmission sizes. The empirical findings validate the framework’s potential for real-world applications in intelligent transportation systems, offering a scalable and privacy-preserving solution for \ac{VFL} environments.

